<div class="column middle">
  <br><h1>The Italian Job</h1>
  <hr style='float: right; width:100%;'>
  <br>
  
  <p>
  A classic heist movie. Nothing more, nothing less.
  </p>
  <p>
  From the very beginning the audience is instantly captured by the action-packed initial heist. A betrayal from one of the members then sets up the premise for the rest of the movie. Although following a fairly cliché format - scope out target, prepare for heist, something goes wrong in the execution of the heist, a hidden factor gets the job done - The Italian Job nevertheless does it very well. 
  </p>
  <p>
  Unfortunately, like many heist movies, just a little bit too much relies on unrealistic hacking and technology; in this instance, the manipulation of every traffic light in the whole of LA. However, what was done well was the opening of the vault - as in a typical heist movie, one member of the team is the safecracker, but in this instance, by making that particular member's occupation be a 'security and vault specialist', this suddenly becomes a bit more feasible.
  </p>
  <p>
  Acting was fine; characters were all likable enough - my only gripe here was that the main mastermind, Charlie Crocker (played by Mark Wahlberg), was smooth without being that likable... if I'm being perfectly honest, kind of boring. On the other hand, Steve (played by Edward Norton) was utterly excellent, being totally annoying and hate-able in the best way possible.
  </p>
  <p>
  Because The Italian Job follows somewhat of a cliché, there really isn't much to the depth of the plot. Though its integrity is sound enough, it is in a word just a bit... basic? In the end though, this doesn't matter too much; the action throughout keeps the pace nicely and overall makes for highly entertaining viewing.</p>
  </p>
  <p>
  7.3/10
  </p>
  <br>
